{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Kate Micucci | image = File:Kate Micucci cropped.png | alt = | caption = Kate Micucci in 2009 at the Steve Allen theater. | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|3|31}} | birth_place = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]], U.S. | residence = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S. | occupation = Actress, voice actress, comedian, singer, songwriter, artist | yearsactive = 2001–present | spouse = {{marriage|[[Jake Sinclair (musician)|Jake Sinclair]]|2018}} }}
'''Kate Micucci''' ({{IPAc-en|m|ᵻ|ˈ|k|u:|tʃ|i}} {{respell|mi|KOO|chee}}; born March 31, 1980) is an American actress, voice actress, comedian, singer, songwriter and artist that is one half of the musical comedy duo ''[[Garfunkel and Oates]]''. Some of her well known roles include [[Stephanie Gooch]] in ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', [[List of Raising Hope characters#Shelley|Shelley]] in ''[[Raising Hope]]'', Lucy in ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'', Sadie in ''[[Steven Universe]]'', Sara Murphy in ''[[Milo Murphy's Law]]'', Daisy in ''[[Nature Cat]]'', [[Clayface]] in ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'', [[Velma Dinkley]] in ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'', [[Webby Vanderquack]] in ''[[DuckTales (2017 TV series)|DuckTales]]'', and Dr. Fox in ''[[Unikitty!]]''.
==Early life== Born in [[Jersey City, New Jersey]], of Italian ancestry,<ref>[http://www.earwolf.com/episode/dragon-boy-suede-and-oates/ Dragon Boy Suede and Oates, episode #31 of Who Charted? on Earwolf<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Micucci was raised in [[Nazareth, Pennsylvania]], in the [[Lehigh Valley]] region of the state, where she first learned to play [[classical piano]], taught by her mother.<ref>Kelly Montgomery, "Inside a Songwriter's Psyche", 2009 December 18 "{{cite web |url=http://press.jordanwhitemusic.com/psyche.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713120120/http://press.jordanwhitemusic.com/psyche.htm |archivedate=July 13, 2011 |df= }}" 2010 September 1</ref> She graduated in 1998 from [[Nazareth Area High School]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[The Express-Times]] |title=Nazareth alum set for 'Scrubs' role |first=Dustin |last=Schoof |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=March 25, 2010 |url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/entertainment/index.ssf?/base/entertainment-0/123329200084130.xml&coll=3 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626220238/http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/entertainment/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fentertainment-0%2F123329200084130.xml&coll=3 |archivedate=June 26, 2009 |df= }}</ref> Micucci then received an [[Associate of Arts|A.A.]] in Fine Arts from [[Keystone College]] in [[La Plume Township, Pennsylvania|La Plume, Pennsylvania]], and a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Studio Art in 2003<ref>[http://www.lmu.edu/Asset5631.aspx 2003 Commencement Program] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119090855/http://www.lmu.edu/Asset5631.aspx |date=November 19, 2009 }} [[Loyola Marymount University]] 2003</ref> from [[Loyola Marymount University]], [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]].
==Career== <!-- can these at least be in date order, instead of which thing people liked best? - Lexein --> Micucci's TV credits include numerous television commercials, as well as Toni the barista on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Four Kings]]'', guest roles on ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', ''[['Til Death]]'', ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[Cory in the House]]'', and ''[[Campus Ladies]]'', and recurring roles on ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'' and ''[[Raising Hope]]''. Her film credits include ''[[The Last Hurrah (2010 film)|The Last Hurrah]]'', ''[[Bart Got a Room]]'' and ''[[When in Rome (2010 film)|When in Rome]]''. She plays "Lily the IT girl" on ''Elevator'' produced by [[HBO]]'s Runawaybox.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/elevatorshow "Elevator Show channel"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312045554/http://www.youtube.com/elevatorshow |date=March 12, 2010 }} [[YouTube]]</ref> In early 2009, she released a five-track [[Extended play|EP]] entitled ''Songs''.<ref name="cdbaby">{{cite web| title=Kate Micucci - ''Songs'' EP| url=http://www.CDBaby.com/cd/katemicucci| publisher=CD Baby}}</ref>
Micucci appeared in five episodes of ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'' ("[[My Lawyer's in Love]]", "[[My Absence]]", "[[My Chief Concern]]", "[[Our Histories]]", and "[[My Finale]]") as [[Stephanie Gooch]], a [[ukulele]] player with whom [[Ted Buckland]] begins a relationship. She performs her song "Mr. Moon" as well as an adapted version of "Fuck You" (retitled "Screw You" for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]), a song she typically performs as part of the musical duo [[Garfunkel and Oates]]. In 2009, she starred in the short film ''[[Imaginary Larry]]'', co-written and co-directed by [[Riki Lindhome]], her partner in Garfunkel and Oates. In August 2009, Micucci appeared in an advertising campaign for [[Hillshire Farms]] and for [[H & R Block]] in January 2010.
[[File:Garfunkel-Oates.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Performing as [[Garfunkel And Oates]] with [[Riki Lindhome]] at [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theater]] in 2009]] Micucci performs "Playin' with Micucci" on third Mondays at the Steve Allen Theater on [[Hollywood Boulevard]], in [[Hollywood, California]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://steveallentheater.com/main/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/micucci.gif |title=Selected posters - Playin' with Micucci |publisher= Steve Allen Theater|accessdate= October 17, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=May 2013}}</ref> most recently in August<ref>{{cite web|url=http://steveallentheater.com/main/?page_id=269 |title=Season Program| pages=22–23 |publisher=Steve Allen Theater |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> and October 2011.<ref>[http://steveallentheater.tix.com/Event.asp?Event=402453 "Playin' with Micucci - October 17, 2011"]. Steve Allen Theater.</ref> In the act, she presents "songs and stories in [a] musical variety show."<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Steve Allen Theater |title=Playin' with Micucci |url=http://steveallentheater.com/micucci/ |accessdate=September 7, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422145058/http://steveallentheater.com/micucci |archivedate=April 22, 2009 |df= }} {{failed verification|date=October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://events.dailynews.com/los-angeles-ca/events/show/211419686-playin-with-micucci |title=Playin' With Micucci |date=October 2011 |work=Los Angeles Events |publisher=''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' |accessdate=October 5, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120718014649/http://events.dailynews.com/los-angeles-ca/events/show/211419686-playin-with-micucci |archivedate=July 18, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Micucci says the title is the only dirty aspect of the show. She can also frequently be seen performing with Lindhome in "An Evening with Garfunkel and Oates" at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theater]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre |title=Los Angeles Performers: Kate Micucci |url=http://losangeles.ucbtheatre.com/talent/view/8278 |accessdate=September 7, 2009}}</ref> She performed with [[William H. Macy]] on the ukulele to promote the [[DVD]] release of the film ''[[Bart Got a Room]]''. The video has been circulated around the [[Internet]] on sites such as [[YouTube]] and ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Huffington Post |title='It's Time To Get Laid': Kate Micucci And William H. Macy Sing About Sex |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/07/29/its-time-to-get-laid-kate_n_247101.html |date=July 29, 2009 |accessdate=September 7, 2009 |first=Alex |last=Leo}}</ref>
In 2010, Micucci appeared in the [[Kristen Bell]] film ''[[When in Rome (2010 film)|When in Rome]]'' and also in an episode in the sixth season of the TV show ''[[Weeds (TV Series)|Weeds]]'' as a slightly sedated waitress. She appeared in some episodes of the [[HBO]] series, ''[[Bored to Death]]'' and appeared as the [[babysitter]]/[[dogsitter]]/eldersitter [[List of Raising Hope characters#Shelley|Shelley]] in the series ''[[Raising Hope]]''. In February 2011, Micucci appeared briefly in a [[Progressive Insurance]] ad as a waitress.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://blogs.mcall.com/tvwatchers/2011/03/nazareths-kate-micucci-in-progressive-ad.html |title=Nazareth's Kate Micucci in Progressive ad |publisher=McAll.com|date= March 2011 }}</ref> She has also voiced a character on [[Pendleton Ward]]'s animated series ''[[Adventure Time]]'', as well as the character of Julie Kane on the [[Disney XD]] animated series ''[[Motorcity]]''. She also voices the recurring character Sadie on the Cartoon Network animated series ''[[Steven Universe]]''. In July 2012, Kate appeared in Written by a Kid's production ''Scary Smash'', a [[Geek and Sundry]] creation that was executive produced by Kim Evey, [[Felicia Day]], and Sheri Byrant.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Dread Central]] |title=Watch the First Episode of Written by a Kid - Scary Smash |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/57434/watch-first-episode-written-kid-scary-smash |date=July 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019054323/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/57434/watch-first-episode-written-kid-scary-smash |archivedate=October 19, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
In January 2013, Micucci's casting was announced for a recurring role on ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'' as "a potential love interest for ... [[Rajesh Koothrappali|Raj]]."<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |title='The Big Bang Theory': 'Raising Hope' Actress to Play Love Interest for Raj (Exclusive) |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/big-bang-theory-raising-hope-416864/ |date=January 2013}}</ref> Her character, the painfully shy Lucy, first appeared on February 14, 2013. Micucci appeared as a guest judge on ''[[King of the Nerds]]''.
As of October 2015 she provides the voice of [[Velma Dinkley]] in the series ''[[Be Cool, Scooby-Doo!]]'', briefly sharing with [[Mindy Cohn]] in other forms of media before taking over full-time.
In 2016, she appeared in Season 1, Episode 6 in the Netflix comedy-drama series, ''[[Easy (TV series)|Easy]]'' along with [[Orlando Bloom]] and [[Malin Åkerman|Malin Akerman]].
==Personal life== Micucci married musician and recording producer [[Jake Sinclair (musician)|Jake Sinclair]] in February of 2018.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.instagram.com/p/BfSNCo2lFBf/?taken-by=lindseybyrnes|title=Just Marrfied|publisher= lindseybyrnes|accessdate= May 3, 2018 }} </ref>
